# TypeScript Standards

- **Strict mode on.** No `any` — use `unknown` + narrowing. No non-null `!` without a written reason.
- Public functions have **explicit return types**; type all boundaries (no implicit `any`).
- Prefer `type`/`interface` from inferred Zod schemas (`z.infer`) so runtime and compile-time agree — one source of truth.
- **Naming:** `camelCase` (vars/functions), `PascalCase` (types/classes/components), `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` (constants), `kebab-case` file names. `snake_case` only in the DB.
- Small, single-responsibility, pure-where-possible functions. Isolate side effects.
- **No magic numbers/strings** — name constants or read from config.
- Comments explain **why**, not what. No narration comments. Delete dead code, don't comment it out.
- Imports ordered: node builtins → external → internal. No unused imports/vars.
- Avoid default exports for modules with multiple symbols; prefer named exports.
- Use discriminated unions + exhaustive `switch` (with `never` check) for state/variant handling.

```typescript
// ✅ exhaustive handling
function label(s: OrderStatus): string {
  switch (s) {
    case 'PENDING': return 'Pending';
    case 'ACCEPTED': return 'Accepted';
    // ...all cases...
    default: { const _exhaustive: never = s; return _exhaustive; }
  }
}
```
